post_text:
Safety precautions required at all UIL contests

The UIL recently announced that schools not enforcing social distancing and masks at all UIL contests may be open to sanctions, including, but not limited to forfeiture of contests.

At Commerce ISD contests, we will have seating on every other row in the gym as well as in the stadium. We will mark rows that aren't available for seating on the ends of the row with blue tape. We are also required to make multiple announcements regarding the UIL rules. Please follow these guidelines. Failure to follow these procedures will result in you being asked to leave the contest.

Our goal is to keep our students and fans safe. We want to ensure that our students do not have to forfeit any contest. Our students deserve to have the full educational experience and following these procedures helps us to provide them that opportunity. We hope to see you at the game!

Charlie Alderman, Superintendent

post_text: School starts on August 4. Register now. Plans are being finalized and will be presented to the Board of Trustees for approval Monday night. Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to free or reduced-price meals due to school closures. Eligible P-EBT families will receive application instructions from schools in late May. The P-EBT application will open the first week of June.
P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and children who are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. For more information, visit: hhs.texas.gov/PEBT

post_text:
Free food service for children starts March 17

Beginning Tuesday, March 17, Commerce ISD Food Services will be providing FREE meals for ALL CISD students AND any community children who are under the age of 18. Meals will be available for pick-up each Monday – Friday from
7:30 a.m. -8:30 a.m for breakfast, and 11:30-12:30 for lunch. until further notice.

Students will be able to pick up one meal at the time listed
above. Children must be present upon pickup.

Pick-up areas are as follows:

A.C. Williams Elementary
615 Culver St.
Curbside grab-and-go
Please go to the east side of A.C.Williams building by the cafeteria

First Baptist Church
1404 Washington St.

Linda Muller Community Center
450 Wheeler Dr.

Norris Community Center
1007 Ross St.

Thank you for letting us be a service at this time to your family and to the Community of Commerce.

post_text:
From Chief of Police Joe Venable:

UPDATE ON THIS MORNINGS POLICE ACTIVITY AT CHS

This morning, we rushed to get information out to parents and others as fast as possible. In doing so, we failed to confirm if a LOCKDOWN had been initiated. We were told and believed that a “HOLD IN PLACE” had been initiated instead. Upon further investigation, it was found that a LOCKDOWN order had indeed been given and was followed by staff and students. Furthermore, it appears that the release of the LOCKDOWN was handled appropriately according to procedures.

Everything else in our original tweet is accurate.

CISD Police Department strives to maintain as safe and secure environment as we possibly can. We were mistaken in our original tweet and apologize for the confusion.
text:
From Chief of Police Joe Venable:

UPDATE ON THIS MORNINGS POLICE ACTIVITY AT CHS

This morning, we rushed to get information out to parents and others as fast as possible. In doing so, we failed to confirm if a LOCKDOWN had been initiated. We were told and believed that a “HOLD IN PLACE” had been initiated instead. Upon further investigation, it was found that a LOCKDOWN order had indeed been given and was followed by staff and students. Furthermore, it appears that the release of the LOCKDOWN was handled appropriately according to procedures.

Everything else in our original tweet is accurate.

CISD Police Department strives to maintain as safe and secure environment as we possibly can. We were mistaken in our original tweet and apologize for the confusion.

post_text:
Parents / Guardians of Commerce Elementary School - ACE/BGC members:

ACE/ BGC programming at Commerce Elementary School will be cancelled for Monday, 10/28/19 due to the events that occurred on Saturday, 10/26/19, in Greenville.

CES ACE/BGC has several staff members that are directly affected.
We are sorry for any inconvenience that this may cause you.

Commerce ISD, ACE and the Boys and Girls Club of Northeast Texas are working to provide support for both CISD students as well as our Youth Development Workers that are largely students of Texas A&M University-Commerce.

CES Parents, please send notice of the plans for your student by way of a note that is signed by you and contains parent/guardian contact information.

During my twenty years of service in the United States Navy, I had the opportunity to lead and mentor hundreds of sailors both professionally and personally. I enjoy working with young people and I am excited about teaching 7th Grade Texas History in Commerce. “Go Tigers!”**

Commerce Middle School
July 22, 2019 at 10:47 AM ·

Please help me welcome Mrs. Bunch to our CMS campus!

**My name is Jennifer Bunch, and I am the new 6th grade English teacher at Commerce Middle School. I am married to a wonderful man named Shay, and I have a sweet, one year old son named Mason. This is my 8th year teaching. I taught middle school for five years and high school for two before coming to Commerce ISD. I have always known that I wanted to be a teacher because I love helping others. I love building relationships with my students and watching them grow and succeed. I am so excited to be at Commerce Middle School for this upcoming school year!**

June 4, 2019 at 12:09 PM ·

I was pleased to officially announce this year's Rising Lone Star winners from high schools across the 4th District of Texas today. These students were nominated by their principals, administrators or counselors for exhibiting outstanding leadership or service in their schools and communities.

I'd like to congratulate them for standing out as the best and brightest in their class. I wish them the best of luck in their future endeavors as they graduate high school, and I’m confident they’ll go on to make Texas’ 4th District very proud.

post_text: We ASPIRE to do more at Commerce ISD!
shared_text:
Texas A&M University-Commerce
March 1, 2019 at 7:00 PM ·

Last week, the university community gathered for an update on the ASPIRE program. Participant Kamdyn Mills had an opportunity to discuss her program experience with the audience. "As a fourth-grade student at AC Williams Elementary school, I am here today to express how grateful I am for the ASPIRE program. The Summer Experience was a great program that kept me and other students learning and building on previous life skills," she said. The program is in its second year and is focused on enriching the lives of Commerce ISD K-16 students through innovative programs and experiences.
text:
We ASPIRE to do more at Commerce ISD!

Texas A&M University-Commerce
March 1, 2019 at 7:00 PM ·

Last week, the university community gathered for an update on the ASPIRE program. Participant Kamdyn Mills had an opportunity to discuss her program experience with the audience. "As a fourth-grade student at AC Williams Elementary school, I am here today to express how grateful I am for the ASPIRE program. The Summer Experience was a great program that kept me and other students learning and building on previous life skills," she said. The program is in its second year and is focused on enriching the lives of Commerce ISD K-16 students through innovative programs and experiences.

shared_text:
Rep. John Ratcliffe
February 27, 2019 at 12:55 PM ·

Today my office is opening up submissions for the annual Congressional Art Competition from high school students in Texas' 4th District.

Last year's winner, "Wheat Fields of Texas,” which was submitted by Jennifer Cogswell from Texoma Christian School, has been on display in the U.S. Capitol Building for the past year. I'm looking forward to seeing this year's entries, as we seek to continue proudly representing the creative talent of Northeast Texas at our nation's Capitol.

More information on how to enter this year's competition is available here: https://ratcliffe.house.gov/services/art-competition.htm

Commerce ISD Police Department
December 19, 2018 at 1:21 PM ·

Commerce ISD Police Chief Joe Venable this morning collaborated with the Hunt County African American Leadership Conference’s “Project Sweet Treats” at Commerce Elementary School, in which HCAALC members ride along with local police officers handing out sweets to children and families with the purpose of improving perceptions of police.

“Building positive relationships starts early”, said Chief Venable. “This is the best part of my job.”

The Commerce ISD Police Department is committed to excellence through active involvement and protection of the community we serve.

All district counselors were called to the campus at around 2:45 p.m. If a parent of an AC Williams student wishes to visit, we will have counselors and administrators at the school in the morning. If a student wants to speak with a counselor, we welcome them to do so.

The incident is under investigation. The safety of our students is our #1 priority.

post_text:
From Officer Dave Contreras with the Commerce ISD Police K9 Unit in Texas:

K9 Coco and I were selected as one of the 30 finalists across the United States in a popularity-vote contest to win a brand-new police Chevy Tahoe equipped for K9 transport.

Our current vehicle is in need of constant repairs and the safety of K9 Coco is very important.

She is the only pitbull in the contest!

She is a two-year-old pit mix rescued from the Pflugerville (TX) Animal Shelter. She was given a second chance at life and she is now trained in narcotics detection. She serves as an ambassador to her breed, which is often stigmatized, and to shelter dogs. Shelter dogs are the best dogs!

Please vote for K9 Coco at vik9s.org/suvvote

Please vote every day! Please share with all your friends!

Officer Dave Contreras #210, K9 Unit

Glenda Henderson is feeling proud with Steve Drummond and 5 others at Commerce High School.
October 1, 2018 at 10:13 PM · Commerce, TX ·

CHS had the opportunity to induct 61 new seniors/juniors into the National Honor Society tonight! This is one of the largest to induct into the program since I have been the sponsor of the group! We will have 92 students in NHS this year. They are outstanding young men and women and we are all blessed to be able to teach at CHS. These students are the best of the best and the heart and soul of Commerce High School! #awesomekiddos

shared_text:
Commerce ISD Police Department
September 11, 2018 at 7:53 AM ·

This morning at approximately 7:31AM, the Commerce ISD Police Department was notified of a fire alarm activation at Commerce Elementary School (CES). Commerce ISD Police Department, along with Commerce Police Department and Commerce Fire Department responded to the location. Despite the inconvenient time of student drop-off at the beginning of the school day, the building was evacuated in a very quick and efficient manner. Through investigation, it was determined that there was no fire or any other threat to safety present. All activities then resumed as normal. This was not a planned fire drill.

shared_text:
Glenda Henderson is feeling grateful with Kyra Stuckmeyer and 7 others.
July 10, 2018 at 10:59 PM ·

Looking forward to the Senior Leadership at CHS this year especially our Senior Class Officers, Student Body Officers and our National Honor Society officers!! These three groups overlap with some of the same students and we find all of them working our NHS Service Projects!

I wanted to go ahead and let you know about a special service project we have coming up in August! I hope to be able to meet with you kiddos before school starts and when I get over this surgery! I should be much better after doctor's appointment next Tuesday.

Service Project:
August 17, 2018 from 6-10pm. We will be helping Coach Reynolds and Mrs. Reynolds with a special night at their church in Greenville. We will be at Grace Community Church and I need about 20 students to help! If you think you can help please let me know. Most all of you have my cell number or you can reply here. Let me know if you would like to help!!! Mrs. H loves you all!

post_text: Glenda Henderson, the best of the best!
shared_text:
Glenda Henderson is with Kathleen Sullivan Hooten and 2 others at Texas A&M University-Commerce.
March 8, 2018 at 11:49 PM · Commerce, TX ·

Tonight was the Commerce Chamber of Commerce banquet. I was asked by my principal to be there to receive a community service award for my NHS students. I had no idea that instead I was awarded employee of the year for Commerce High School by the Chamber of Commerce. I was nominated by my principal. I was in total surprise. I was speechless and I’m sure that’s hard for some of you to believe!!!!!! Thank you Mr. Drummond so very much. I was humbled by your words that were read and I thank you for your kindness. God bless you sir and my friend!!!

t's not too late! Need a gift this week to show you care? Say, "Happy Valentine's Day!" to any CISD student, CISD teacher, CISD/BGC staff member with a beautiful live carnation, for just $2, delivered on February 14th!!

Place an order today (2/12) or tomorrow (2/13) to be delivered to any CISD campus, Central Office, and/or Bus Barn. Orders for family members of students can also be delivered to CISD students.

To place your order, stop by ACW or complete the attached order form and return to ACW along with $2 per flower. For rush orders, email attached form to racheal.bailey@commerceisd.org and send money to ACW by Feb 14th. Duplicate form as necessary.

Thank you for your support of ACW!
